post_text:
Hello to all,

I am pleased to announce after a challenging and engaging interview process, Mr. Jeffery Harrison was hired as our new superintendent this evening.

We are very excited to welcome Mr. Harrison to our Buckeye family. The board appreciates the staff and community feedback on the finalists which was received during the town hall meeting with the top candidates last Tuesday.

We feel confident Mr. Harrison is the right person for this very important position. The board was very impressed with him. We feel he has what we were looking for leading us into the future. He is a person with many great attributes. We are very fortunate to have him lead our district into the future.

We know Mr. Harrison is going to work hard for the district and he will make sure that we move the district forward. Mr. Harrison is a people person. It certainly will not take long for him to meet everyone and begin building relationships and trust.

Thank you,

Denise Piovarchy
President
Buckeye Board of Education

post_text: Ellianna Newman (incoming 6th grader) competed in the 2020 Ohio Invention League State Fair competition in July and was named the Innovator Award for Transportation with her invention "Criminal Catcher". Congratulations to Ellie!

post_text:
A Buckeye Board of Education Special Event will take place from 5:00-8:00 pm on Tuesday, August 11, 2020 at Buckeye High School, 3084 Columbia Road, Medina. The purpose of the meeting is to provide the public the opportunity to meet each of the three final Buckeye Superintendent candidates. Each candidate will have separate individual question and answer sessions with community members, staff and school administrators. An online survey will be available for attendees to complete for feedback.

The Buckeye Board of Education will have their regular Board Meeting at 8:30pm on August 11, 2020 in the Buckeye High School Auditorium, 3084 Columbia Road, Medina.

post_text:
Good Evening,

The Buckeye School Reopening Committee has been working together to present the Buckeye Board of Education recommendations for reopening of school options in the fall. The administrative team appreciates the feedback and work of the parents, staff and community members who are serving on the committee. It is our belief that families need to be aware of the options and ideas that are being discussed and possibly submitted to the Board of Education. Our reopening plan is a work in progress. Both options will be offered to families and a form will be sent out in the first week of August for parents interested in signing up for the Virtual Learning Academy. We will continue to communicate through this evolving situation that faces our community.

I hope this finds everyone safe and well,

Sincerely,

Dawn Kochanek, Administrator Assigned to the Buckeye School Reopening Plan

post_text: Due to school closures, Buckeye will not be able to host in person Camp Invention this year. We are going to host a new at home program offered by The National Inventor's Hall of Fame, Camp Invention Connect, which includes home activity kits delivered to your home with digital enhancements. If you have already registered for Buckeye's Camp Invention, you will be contacted directly by Camp Invention in the coming weeks regarding changing to the new program or receiving a refund. If you have not registered or are interested in learning more about the new program, you may learn more and register at https://www.invent.org/camp-invention-connect.

post_text: Happy Friday Buckeye! There has been a lot of discussion about graduation recently both among our community and at the state level. It is important to us to honor our graduates' accomplishments and to wish them well as they leave our campus. As you may know, a survey went out earlier this week for parents and students asking for feedback on a few possibilities. We are also aware of guidance provided yesterday by the Ohio Department of Education. At this time, we are still reviewing and weighing options to determine next steps. Please look for additional information from Superintendent Morgan as soon as it is available.

post_text:
B.L.E.A. Teacher Scholarship

The Buckeye Local Education Association is accepting applications for its annual scholarship for aspiring teachers. To be eligible, candidates must meet the following requirements:
(1) A student must have completed at least 132 quarter hours or 88 semester hours of college credit by June 2020.
(2) The student must be majoring in some area of education.
(3) The student must be a graduate of Buckeye High School.

Applications are available online on the Buckeye Local Schools webpage. http://www.buckeyeschools.org/index.php/flyercentral The completed application and recommendation letter from a B.L.E.A. member must be returned to the board office no later than June 30, 2020. If preferred, you can also scan and email the application and recommendation letter to Emily Goodwin.

If you know of any eligible students, please relay this information to them. If you have any questions, you may contact Emily Goodwin at egoodwin@buckeyeschools.org.

Happy Census Day!

How the 2020 Census Affects Children
The 2020 Census count impacts the federal funds that communities receive each year for programs and services that are critical for schools, students, and younger children, such as:

Special education, Head Start, after-school programs, and classroom technology.
Food assistance, including free and reduced-price school lunches.
Maternal and child health programs.

Reminder: Online instruction begins tomorrow. It's important that we all be patient with one another as we are all navigating new territory.

Also, please see the message from Mr. Morgan last week, March 25, for reminders about this week's device and food pickup.

Device pickup is tomorrow, 3/30, for K-6 families who have already contacted their school office to indicate a need. As a reminder, please bring your own pen for signing out the device. Packets will also be available for grades PreK-6 for families who do not have access to WiFi at home.

This Thursday, there will not be food delivery. Instead, all families are welcome to pick up food between noon and 6:00 p.m. by pulling around to the back of the elementary (the car rider area).

post_text:
We will be checking out one device per family for use during the period that school is closed and online learning may be utilized. Students in grades 7-12 already have a 1:1 Chromebook that comes home. Students in Grades K-6 who do not have a sibling in grades 7-12, and do not have a device to utilize at home, may contact Amy Doty (adoty@buckeyeschools.org) to request one device for their family to use. Please include the student's name , grade and homeroom teacher in your request. Families will need access to wifi in order to use the device.

Requested devices may be picked up Monday, March 30, 2020. The drive through device pickup will be held in the Intermediate Building Bus Loop from 7:00 am - 6:00 pm. Parents will need to sign the agreement form, then will be given a device to borrow. Please bring a signed agreement with you or your own pen if you need to sign the agreement.

Families of students in K-6 without wifi access may pick up a paper packet on Monday March 30 in the Intermediate Bus Loop from 7:00 am - 6:00 pm .

post_text:
Thank you to F.I.T., especially HR and Administration Manager Jennifer Connelly and Senior Vice President Hal Wagoner, our third grade teachers and principal, and Dave Parish for planning today’s 3rd grade field trip to F.I.T. In Vally City! Students were able to tour the manufacturing plant and have hands on experience in precision machining.

Did you know F.I.T. supplies wheel, lock, and flare nut parts as well as pipes to automotive companies? Ohio is actually the number one producer of engines and the number two manufacturer of transmissions in North America. Students were able to learn more about how a local company’s products are distributed far beyond Ohio!

post_text: Thank you to Brunswick High School and the Medina County Career Center for hosting. In partnership with the MCCC, Buckeye currently offers two high school level BioMed classes: Principles of Biomedical Science and Human Body Systems. Next year, Medical Interventions will also be offered.
shared_text:
Brunswick City Schools
February 5 at 11:40 PM ·

Today Brunswick High School, in collaboration with the Medina County Career Center, hosted a Project Lead the Way (PLTW) “BioMed Day”. Local medical professionals spoke with high school students from Brunswick, Medina and Buckeye about their education and career. PLTW provides students a hands-on, transformative learning experience that develops real world problem solving skills. PLTW curriculum focuses on science, technology, engineering and math. Brunswick High School is one of 6 high schools in Ohio to earn the designation of PLTW “Distinguished School”. #MCCC

post_text: Earlier this year, BHS student, Jacob Canedy, was nominated by his private voice instructor for the Honors Performance Series at Carnegie Hall. Jacob has been selected out of an incredibly competitive pool of international applicants to appear at Carnegie Hall in New York City as part of a vocal performance that will take place this February. Jacob will join other high school students from all over the world in collaboration of a performance. Jacob’s Carnegie Hall debut is due in part to the excellent music education that he has received from Ms. Pam Haberkorn who has truly cultivated a music program at Buckeye that the entire district should celebrate.

post_text:
Please see the message below that went out to parents yesterday about internet security:

Dear Parents,

Our school uses Securly to filter access to non-academic websites, as well as alert school personnel of flagged activity. Flagged activity scans social media, sites visited, and web searches, and flags items that indicate bullying, self-harm or suicide. Starting November 22, 2019 school personnel will monitor the alerts during school hours and address flagged alerts as appropriate. Alerts that occur outside of school hours will be addressed the next school day.

As part of the solution, we have given you access to the free Parent Portal and SecurlyHOME app. On November 22, 2019, you will receive a “Welcome Email” from Securly, and you will be able to download the App. You’ll also start to receive a weekly email report each Monday containing a sample of your child’s online activity from the previous week.
